            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/approvals"]""",
            Tags = """["approvals","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Approvals — Advanced Reference\n\nDeeper notes for approvers and managers who want to run approvals smoothly. This covers where the requests in your inbox come from, why some things never land there at all, and the day-to-day tips and gotchas of setting up and living with approval workflows.\n\n## How a Request Reaches Your Inbox\n\nYou never create an approval request by hand. It's born the moment someone submits the thing being approved — a buyer submits a purchase order, an employee turns in an expense, a salesperson sends a quote for sign-off. At that point the app looks for an approval workflow set up for that kind of request. If one is turned on, it creates the request, drops it on Step 1, and routes it to whoever that step names. That person sees it in their inbox; you see it in yours only when a step points at you.\n\n- **One workflow per kind of request.** Keep a single active workflow for each thing you approve — one for purchase orders, one for expenses, and so on. Two active workflows competing for the same kind of request only causes confusion about which one runs.\n- **Your inbox is only yours.** The inbox shows the requests waiting on you and no one else. There's no company-wide \"all requests\" list on this screen — that keeps your queue to just the decisions that are actually yours to make.\n\n## Why Some Requests Never Need Sign-Off\n\nNot every purchase order or expense should stop for approval. The Amount Threshold on a workflow is how you draw that line.\n\n- **Below the threshold, the request skips approval entirely.** If your PO workflow has a $500 threshold and a $300 order is submitted, no request is ever created — the order just proceeds. The buyer isn't blocked and nothing lands in anyone's inbox. Set the threshold where routine, low-risk spend flows without you, and only the amounts worth a look reach you.\n- **Auto-approve keeps small stuff moving.** Inside a step, Auto-Approve Below does the same favor one level down: a request under that amount is approved on its own and shows as AutoApproved, so trivial amounts don't sit waiting on a person. Use it for the long tail of tiny requests you'd rubber-stamp anyway.\n- **The two work together.** The threshold decides whether a request enters the workflow at all; auto-approve decides whether a request that did enter clears a given step without a human. Tune both so your inbox holds real decisions, not noise.\n\n## Tips and Gotchas When Running Workflows\n\n- **Escalation is your safety net, not a punishment.** Set Escalate After (Hours) on any step where a stalled request causes real pain — a rush PO, a customer-facing quote. If the step sits too long, the request escalates on its own instead of quietly rotting in someone's inbox while they're on vacation. Leave it off for low-urgency steps.\n- **Pick the right approver type.** \"Specific User\" pins the step to one named person — clean, but a single point of failure if they're out. \"Role\" spreads it to anyone holding that role, so coverage survives an absence. \"Manager\" follows the org chart to the requester's own boss, which is ideal when who signs off depends on who asked. Match the type to how you actually want coverage to work.\n- **Order your steps from cheapest to most senior.** Put the quick, local sign-off first and the higher authority last. That way most requests are caught and fixed early, and only the ones that pass the first gate ever reach a senior approver's inbox.\n- **A rejection ends the road — say why.** Rejecting is terminal: the request stops and won't move forward, so the requester has to start over. Because of that, the reason you type is the whole message they get. Be specific — \"vendor not on the approved list, use Acme instead\" saves a round-trip that \"no\" never will.\n- **Approving is a decision, not a formality.** Once you approve the final step the request is done and can't be walked back from here. Review the summary, the amount, and who asked before you click — especially on the last step, where your approval is what makes it real.\n- **Turn a workflow off instead of over-tuning it.** If a workflow is causing more friction than it's worth, an Active / Inactive state lets you park it without losing its setup. An inactive workflow stops catching new requests but keeps its steps for when you want it back.\n","sections":[]}"""
